    "summary": "The Parthenon (447–432 BC) is the supreme monument of the Athenian Golden Age — a Doric temple to Athena Parthenos (the Virgin) on the Acropolis, built under the direction of Pericles with the architects Ictinus and Callicrates and the master sculptor Pheidias. Financed by the tribute of the Delian League (Athens's naval empire), it was simultaneously a temple, a treasury, and a statement of Athenian imperial power and cultural supremacy.\n\nThe Parthenon's architectural refinements make it technically astonishing: its columns lean slightly inward, its horizontal surfaces curve subtly upward toward the center, and the columns bulge imperceptibly at their midpoints (entasis) — all to counteract optical illusions that would otherwise make the building appear to sag. Inside stood Pheidias's chryselephantine (gold and ivory) statue of Athena, approximately 12 meters tall. The frieze running around the building depicted the Panathenaic procession — unusually, a contemporary human scene rather than mythological — and the metopes showed battles between Greeks and centaurs, Lapiths, Amazons, and Trojans, all metaphors for the Greek triumph over Persia. Converted to a church, then a mosque, partially destroyed by a Venetian bombardment in 1687, the Parthenon remains the iconic image of ancient Greece.",
